{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646458"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:31:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:31:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18183"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18183"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.13,0.07,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10897"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79240"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10897"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64582"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25342"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79240"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe genitofemoral nerve is a branch of the lumbar plexus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arises from the L1 and L2 nerve roots and innervates the cremaster muscle","Arises from the L3 and L4 nerve roots and innervates the quadriceps muscle","Arises from the L5 and S1 nerve roots and innervates the gluteus maximus muscle","Arises from the T12 and L1 nerve roots and innervates the abdominal muscles","Arises from the S2 and S3 nerve roots and innervates the perineal muscles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egenitofemoral nerve\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the lumbar plexus, specifically from the L1 and L2 nerve roots. It plays a crucial role in innervating the cremaster muscle, which is responsible for the cremasteric reflex. This reflex involves the contraction of the cremaster muscle in response to stroking the inner thigh, leading to the elevation of the testis. Additionally, the genitofemoral nerve provides sensory innervation to the skin of the anterior scrotum in males and the mons pubis and labia majora in females.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Equadriceps muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is innervated by the femoral nerve, which arises from the L2, L3, and L4 nerve roots, not the L3 and L4 nerve roots alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egluteus maximus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is innervated by the inferior gluteal nerve, which arises from the L5, S1, and S2 nerve roots, not the L5 and S1 nerve roots alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eperineal muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are innervated by the pudendal nerve, which arises from the S2, S3, and S4 nerve roots, not the S2 and S3 nerve roots alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are innervated by the lower intercostal nerves and the subcostal nerve, which arise from the T7 to T12 nerve roots, not the T12 and L1 nerve roots alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The genitofemoral nerve arises from the lumbar plexus, specifically from the L1 and L2 nerve roots.","It innervates the cremaster muscle and provides sensory innervation to the skin of the anterior scrotum in males and the mons pubis and labia majora in females.","The genitofemoral nerve is responsible for the cremasteric reflex, which is the contraction of the cremaster muscle in response to stroking the inner thigh."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64582"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18183"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64582"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T21:01:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T21:02:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10897"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79240"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emed